</section>

<!-- 04 MACHINE TYPES -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02 — Machine Types We Service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Every washer configuration in Los Angeles</h2>
    <p class="lead">The same failure can present differently depending on whether you have a front-loader, top-loader, or stacked unit. Our technicians know the difference and come prepared.</p>

    <div class="type-grid">
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-icon">🔄</div>
        <h3>Front-Load Washers</h3>
        <p>The most common configuration in LA condos and renovated homes. More energy-efficient, but more complex — and more prone to specific issues.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Door gasket mold and deterioration</li>
          <li>Door lock / latch failure (won't start)</li>
          <li>Drum bearing wear (loud grinding)</li>
          <li>Drain pump blockage or failure</li>
          <li>Control board and error codes</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-icon">⬆️</div>
        <h3>Top-Load Washers</h3>
        <p>Common in single-family homes and older rental units throughout LA. Simpler mechanically, with their own set of typical failure points.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Lid switch failure (won't spin or drain)</li>
          <li>Agitator problems</li>
          <li>Water pump and drain issues</li>
          <li>Tub bearing noise</li>
          <li>Drive belt and motor coupling</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-icon">📦</div>
        <h3>Stackable &amp; Combo Units</h3>
        <p>Dominant in West Hollywood, Silver Lake, Culver City, and most of LA's dense rental market. Tight spaces, stacked configurations, often front-loaders on a pedestal or stacked dryer bracket.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>All front-load failure types apply</li>
          <li>Vibration and shaking during spin</li>
          <li>Access constraints require planning</li>
          <li>Pedestal drawer issues</li>
          <li>Stacking kit bracket problems</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-icon">⚡</div>
        <h3>High-Efficiency (HE) Washers</h3>
        <p>Most modern washers — front-load or top-load — are HE. They use less water and more sensors, which means a different diagnostic approach when something goes wrong.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Error code diagnosis (brand-specific)</li>
          <li>Pressure sensor and water level issues</li>
          <li>Excessive vibration from drum imbalance</li>
          <li>Slow fill or no-fill water inlet valve</li>
          <li>Control board failures</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03 — Common Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fix most often</h2>
    <p class="lead">Every repair starts with a real diagnosis — not a parts swap on a guess. We identify the cause, give you a written quote, then fix it.</p>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Washer Not Draining</h3>
        <p>The drain pump is the most common cause — especially on front-loaders where the pump filter gets clogged with lint, coins, and debris. It's the small access panel near the bottom of the machine. Frequently neglected, frequently the culprit. We check it before replacing anything.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Won't Spin or Agitate</h3>
        <p>On top-loaders, a failed lid switch is the first thing to check — the machine won't spin without it. On front-loaders, it's often the door latch, motor coupling, or drive belt. We carry these parts for the brands we see most in LA.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Water Leaking</h3>
        <p>Front-loaders leak most often from a torn or deteriorated door gasket — water gets past the seal on every wash. Top-loaders leak from a failed water pump or cracked hose. Either way, water on a laundry room floor usually means the issue has been developing for a while.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Loud Noise or Vibration</h3>
        <p>Grinding or rumbling during the spin cycle usually points to worn tub bearings — this gets worse over time and eventually damages the drum shaft. Banging or thumping is often an unbalanced load sensor or worn shock absorbers. Neither fixes itself.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Lock / Latch Failure</h3>
        <p>One of the more frustrating failures: the washer won't start because the door latch doesn't register as locked, even though it closes. This is a common front-load failure mode on Samsung, LG, and Electrolux. Usually a straightforward part replacement once diagnosed correctly.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Mold and Odor (Front-Loaders)</h3>
        <p>Front-loaders in LA apartments with limited airflow develop mold on the rubber door gasket and inside the drum. We clean the gasket thoroughly and inspect it for tears — a torn gasket holds water and accelerates mold. If it needs replacement, we carry gaskets for the most common brands on the van.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Error Codes / Won't Start</h3>
        <p>Modern washers display error codes that tell a specific story when you know how to read them. Our technicians are current on diagnostic codes for Samsung, LG, Whirlpool, Bosch, Miele, and Electrolux — these aren't guesses, they point to specific components that need to be tested or replaced.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Control Board Issues</h3>
        <p>A control board failure usually presents as erratic behavior — cycles that won't complete, random error codes, buttons that don't respond. It's one of the pricier repairs, so we verify the board is actually the problem before recommending it. Sometimes what looks like a board failure is a faulty sensor or wiring connection.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 BRANDS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Brands We Service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">From Miele to Maytag — we carry parts for what LA actually has</h2>
    <p class="lead">The washers we see most often in Los Angeles homes, condos, and multi-family buildings. We stock OEM parts for these brands directly from authorized suppliers.</p>

    <div style="margin-top:24px; margin-bottom:18px;">
      <p style="font-size:0.8rem; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.1em; color:#888; margin:0 0 12px; font-weight:700;">Premium &amp; European Brands</p>
      <div class="brands-grid">
        <span class="brand-chip">Miele</span>
        <span class="brand-chip">Bosch</span>
        <span class="brand-chip">Electrolux</span>
        <span class="brand-chip">Asko</span>
        <span class="brand-chip">Blomberg</span>
        <span class="brand-chip">Speed Queen</span>
        <span class="brand-chip">Fisher &amp; Paykel</span>
      </div>
