<!-- 07 RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">05 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">West Hollywood · LG Front-Load Stackable</div>
        <h3>"Washer shakes violently on spin, neighbors complained"</h3>
        <p>Classic issue in WeHo high-rise stacked units: worn shock absorbers on the drum combined with a worn suspension rod. The machine was vibrating through the floor. In a concrete building it's audible two floors down. The root cause was years of off-balance loads slowly wearing out the suspension system.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced all four shock absorbers and two suspension rods with OEM LG parts. Ran a full spin cycle at max load before leaving — vibration eliminated. Customer asked about a dryer vent cleaning while we were there; completed same visit.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Silver Lake · Samsung Front-Load</div>
        <h3>"Door won't lock — gets error code DE every time"</h3>
        <p>DE on a Samsung front-loader is the door error — the door latch assembly isn't registering as locked. Common failure on this model after 4–5 years. Some customers try to override it or force the door; that causes secondary damage to the door strike and occasionally the control board. Caught early, it's a clean fix.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced door latch assembly with OEM Samsung part. Verified error cleared and cycle completed successfully. Took about 45 minutes total.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Culver City · Bosch 500 Series Front-Load</div>
        <h3>"Clothes coming out soaking wet — not spinning properly"</h3>
        <p>The Bosch 500 had a drain pump issue — slow draining meant the drum still had water when the spin cycle started, which the machine detected and throttled back to protect the bearing. Classic sequence: drain pump degrades → incomplete drain → slow spin → clothes still wet. Not obvious without running a diagnostic.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced drain pump with OEM Bosch part, cleared accumulated debris from the pump filter (it was badly clogged — hadn't been cleaned in years), verified full spin at 1200 RPM before closing out.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Pasadena · Miele W1 Front-Load</div>
        <h3>"Loud grinding sound — gets louder every week"</h3>
        <p>Worn tub bearings — a Miele W1 that's seen hard use. The bearings support the drum shaft; when they wear, the drum wobbles slightly on every rotation and the grinding gets progressively worse. Left to run, it eventually damages the drum shaft itself, which turns a bearing job into a significantly more expensive repair.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced rear tub bearing and drum shaft seal. Miele parts sourced from authorized supplier. The repair took longer than average — about 2.5 hours — but the machine runs quietly and the customer avoided what would have been a full drum assembly replacement.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

